<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF207-971-738  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 971 738.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Industrial Computing  Oct 1989 p42(1).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Benefits are 'there to be had'.(Survey report of computer use inindustry.)andM;</TITLE><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Industrial Computing's 1989 survey of computer use andapplications indicates that the greater the commitment given bymanagement, the greater the benefits that can be derived fromcomputerized manufacturing.andP;  Although accurately measuring thesebenefits can be difficult, companies with formal informationtechnology strategies have clearer ideas of which systems reachexpectations and which do not.andP;  Survey respondents say thatcomputer-aided production management, bill of materials, andcapacity requirements planning systems are among manufacturingsystems that have resulted in expected benefits.andP;  CADCAMinstallations are also considered beneficial, but many of thesesystems suffer from 'short-sighted design'.andP;  Such automation asmaterials handling systems, robotics, and automated assemblysystems are currently out of favor.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     SurveyUnited KingdomManufacturingCAD-CAMComputer SystemsManagement of EDPEnd Users.andO;Feature:   illustrationgraph.andO;Caption:   Main objective for installing integrated industrial computingsystems. (graph)andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>